description.plain:
Loski, also known as Drilloski Loose, is a member of Kennington, South London crew Harlem Spartans along with drill icons such as MizOrMac and Bis. He started making music at a young age and went by the name YNizzy, taken from his dad – who used to make music under the name TY Nizzy. He then joined Harlem and changed his name to Loski. His breakthrough tune, “Hazards”, was released in 2016. He was then sent to jail for firearms possession and came out in June 2017 and released major tracks such as “Teddy Bruckshot” and “Money & Beef”.

In 2018, Loski released hit tracks such as “Cool Kid” and “Forrest Gump”, which received over 5 and 10 million views on YouTube respectively, helping to cement him as an artist in the UK scene. His debut album, Call Me Loose, was released at the end of 2018 and showed him branching out into other genres. In 2019 he released his second album Mad Move, featuring “Hazards 2.0” and “No Cap” with DigDat.

Loski was arrested in April 2019 on charges of gun possession and was only released in February 2020, pending a retrial. He soon released “Allegedly” in March and in July dropped “On Me” with MizOrMac. In October 2020 he released Music, Trial & Trauma: A Drill Story with features from icons like [Stormzy}(/artists/Stormzy]), dancehall artist Popcaan and Afrobeats star Davido and just as diverse a range of sounds.

songs.title: Allegedly

description.plain:
Following his very recent release from prison, this song references Loski having allegedly been caught with a loaded firearm at the top of 2019.

With his breezy, choppy flow underpinning Ghosty’s eerie drill beat, Loski reflects on his time behind bars, letting us know that he should’ve been at Wireless and Stormzy’s #Merky Fest, but instead he was locked up watching Love Island.

As expected, the rapper hits us with a number of gully lines, along with references to his alleged crimes that saw him incarcerated, and in the accompanying visuals, Loski can be seen performing the track in a prison setting, before flipping the script and flexing with some expensive cars and high-end designer threads.

As expected, the rapper hits us with a number of gully lines, along with references to his alleged crimes that saw him incarcerated, and in the accompanying visuals, Loski can be seen performing the track in a prison setting, before flipping the script and flexing with some expensive cars and high-end designer threads.

songs.title: Teddy Bruckshot 2

description.plain:
“Teddy Bruckshot 2” plays as the very highly anticipated sequel to Loski’s 2017 banger “Teddy Bruckshot” from his Call Me Loose mixtape.

Sitting on the brooding and fast paced drill beat by Santi Beats, the song’s namesake is one of the singles that shot Loski into superstardom. He has been teasing the drop of the second part for almost three years, and it comes into fruition on his debut studio album.

Essentially being “the old Loski”, we see him ride topics such as making his opps scatter, dealing with firearms, and narrating his time spent as a drug dealer.
